Start backwards and 7 steps, anon.
>Self-revelation, when your character does something to show they've changed.
>Weakness, where the character starts. How they're like at the beginning.
>Desire, what the character wants.
>Opponant, they want the same thing as the mc however what makes them good is they strike the mc in their weakness. In the case of a romance, a waifur would not want to have a romance with the mc because of this weakness.
>plan, the mc does something to get the gal or defeat the badguy. Of course its going to go wrong because of the mc's weakness.
>Battle, where the mc and the opponant or waifur clash. Whether or not the mc wins, they realize from the battle itself that they need to change, resulting in the self revelation
>New equilibrium: What is life like for the mc after their change?

Anonymous Mon 03 May 2021 00:42:07 No.38383063 Report
Quoted By: >>38383377
>>38382331
Sketch out the ending, then work out what happened just before that. Don't write. Make a few brief notes as if you're outlining.
If that sparks something on either end of the story, outline that as well.
You may be 100% wrong, and that's part of the process. Taking a few guesses is part of the process. Like >>38382712 suggests, you need to internalize the structure. It is not a checklist. There are other ways or series of steps. But understanding three and four-part structure, character types, and basic tropes will help you know which parts are relevant to your story.
And the worst part is that you don't know your characters or story until after the first draft.
Don't write an autobiography unless you mean to. Draw from your own experience, and then make a hairpin turn. Treat it as an adventure. If they don't surprise you, or act in ways that you never would, then you will be too self-invested. They aren't you. Play God, not puppetmaster.
